---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";

const DEMO_URL = "https://gen-ui.jeffmills.dev";
const SOURCE_URL = "https://github.com/k0bura/gen-ui-demo";
---

<Base
  title="Gen UI Demo, Jeff Mills"
  description="A two-stage Claude tool-use pipeline that composes UI from a tiny web-component library, without generating any code."
>
  <p class="project-back"><a href="/projects">&laquo; all projects</a></p>
  <h1 class="page-title">gen ui demo</h1>
  <p class="project-meta">
    <span class="project-year">2026</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span class="project-status">live</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>2-day prototype</span>
    <span class="meta-sep">&middot;</span>
    <span>solo</span>
  </p>

  <p class="page-lede">
    Two Claude tool-use calls in series. Stage 1 picks components from a tiny
    web-component library and fills them with content. Stage 2 arranges them
    into a layout. The renderer is plain Svelte. The LLM never writes code.
  </p>

  <aside class="callout">
    <span class="callout-label">The constraint</span>
    <p>
      When I built the original at Vanguard, AI-generated code was off the
      table for production. So the question became: can an LLM compose a UI
      from a known set of trusted components, without writing the code that
      renders them? If yes, the LLM stays in its safe lane (content
      generation, structured selection) and the application code keeps its
      deterministic guarantees.
    </p>
  </aside>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <div class="cta-row">
    <a class="cta-primary" href={DEMO_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
      Open the live demo &raquo;
    </a>
    <a class="cta-secondary" href={SOURCE_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">
      Source on GitHub &nearr;
    </a>
  </div>
  <p class="cta-note">
    The demo runs as a standalone app at
    <code>{DEMO_URL.replace("https://", "")}</code>. Reviewers can clone
    the repo and <code>npm run dev</code> in under a minute.
  </p>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">how it works</h2>

  <div
    class="diagram"
    role="img"
    aria-label="Pipeline: user prompt feeds Stage 1 LLM which picks components and fills content; output is a JSON component list; this feeds Stage 2 LLM which decides layout; output is layout JSON; a Svelte renderer turns both into the final UI."
  >
    <div class="diagram-node">user prompt</div>
    <div class="diagram-arrow">&#9660;</div>
    <div class="diagram-node is-stage">
      <div class="diagram-node-title">stage 1 LLM</div>
      <div class="diagram-node-body">pick components<br />+ fill content</div>
    </div>
    <div class="diagram-arrow">
      &#9660;<br /><span class="diagram-payload">json component list</span>
    </div>
    <div class="diagram-node is-stage">
      <div class="diagram-node-title">stage 2 LLM</div>
      <div class="diagram-node-body">decide layout</div>
    </div>
    <div class="diagram-arrow">
      &#9660;<br /><span class="diagram-payload">layout json</span>
    </div>
    <div class="diagram-node">
      <div class="diagram-node-title">svelte renderer</div>
      <div class="diagram-node-body">deterministic</div>
    </div>
    <div class="diagram-arrow">&#9660;</div>
    <div class="diagram-node">final UI</div>
  </div>

  <dl class="stage-list">
    <dt>Stage 1, content + component selection</dt>
    <dd>
      Anthropic Messages API call with a tool schema describing each
      component (name, description, prop types). The model returns its choices
      as <code>tool_use</code> blocks. The app parses them into a flat array
      of <code>{`{ component, props }`}</code> pairs. The model never returns
      JSX, HTML, or CSS.
    </dd>

    <dt>Stage 2, layout decision</dt>
    <dd>
      Second Messages API call. The component array from Stage 1 is the
      input. The tool schema defines a recursive grid layout
      (<code>type</code>, <code>columns</code>, <code>children</code>,
      <code>span</code>). Output is a single layout object referencing
      components by index.
    </dd>

    <dt>Stage 3, deterministic render</dt>
    <dd>
      A recursive Svelte component walks the layout JSON and renders each
      web component with its filled props. Plain application code. No LLM
      involvement. Predictable, testable, debuggable.
    </dd>
  </dl>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">what this proved</h2>
  <ul class="proof-list">
    <li>
      <strong>The composition / rendering split holds.</strong> The LLM
      reasons about which components and what content; the application code
      draws. Each side is good at its job.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Tool schemas are the contract.</strong> Constraining all model
      output to typed JSON eliminates the code-correctness and injection
      risks that block production use of free-form LLM output.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A well-designed design system is the substrate.</strong>
      Framework-agnostic web components with constrained props were the
      right shape for this years before generative UI was a real category.
      The original prototype validated AXS&rsquo;s architecture as durable
      against the GenAI paradigm shift.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <h2 class="section-title">stack</h2>
  <dl class="stack-list">
    <dt>Frontend</dt>
    <dd>Astro, Svelte 5, Lit web components</dd>
    <dt>Pipeline</dt>
    <dd>Anthropic Messages API, two-stage tool use, async generator stream</dd>
    <dt>Hosting</dt>
    <dd>Cloudflare Pages + Pages Functions</dd>
    <dt>Original prototype</dt>
    <dd>Svelte, Node.js, AWS Bedrock with Claude tool use</dd>
  </dl>

  <hr class="jm-rule" />

  <p class="project-foot">
    Full write-up: <a href="/writing/gen-ui-with-claude-tool-use">Generating UI Without Generating Code</a>
    &middot; <a href={DEMO_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">live demo</a>
    &middot; <a href={SOURCE_URL} target="_blank" rel="noopener">source</a>
  </p>
</Base>

<style>
  .project-back {
    margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
  }

  .page-title {
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    text-transform: lowercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0.4rem;
  }

  .project-meta {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-size: 0.85em;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    align-items: baseline;
  }

  .project-meta .project-year {
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .project-meta .project-status {
    color: var(--jm-color-ok);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .meta-sep {
    color: var(--jm-color-border);
  }

  .page-lede {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .section-title {
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    text-transform: lowercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    margin: 2rem 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .section-lede {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }

  .stage-list,
  .stack-list {
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr;
    gap: 0.4rem 1.25rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .stage-list dt {
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.8em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    padding-top: 0.4rem;
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
  }

  .stage-list dd {
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    grid-column: 1 / -1;
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }

  .stack-list dt {
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 0.78em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    padding-top: 0.15rem;
  }

  .stack-list dd {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }

  @media (max-width: 540px) {
    .stack-list {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.2rem;
    }
    .stack-list dd {
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
  }

  .proof-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding-left: 1.5rem;
    margin: 0.5rem 0 0;
  }

  .proof-list li {
    position: relative;
    margin: 0.6rem 0;
  }

  .proof-list li::before {
    content: ">";
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    position: absolute;
    left: -1.25rem;
  }

  .proof-list strong {
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .project-foot {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    font-size: 0.9em;
  }

  code {
    font-family: var(--jm-font-mono);
    font-size: 0.9em;
    background: #1a1a1a;
    padding: 0.1em 0.35em;
  }

  .cta-row {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin: 1rem 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .cta-primary,
  .cta-secondary {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: 0.65rem 1.1rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    text-decoration: none;
    font-size: 0.95em;
  }

  .cta-primary {
    color: var(--jm-color-bg);
    background: var(--jm-color-accent);
    border: 1px solid var(--jm-color-accent);
  }

  .cta-primary:hover {
    background: var(--jm-color-fg);
    border-color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .cta-secondary {
    color: var(--jm-color-accent);
    border: 1px dashed var(--jm-color-accent);
  }

  .cta-secondary:hover {
    color: var(--jm-color-fg);
    border-color: var(--jm-color-fg);
  }

  .cta-note {
    margin: 0.75rem 0 0;
    color: var(--jm-color-muted);
    font-size: 0.9em;
  }
</style>
